<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
<meta charset="UTF-8">
<meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
<title>Registration Form</title>
</head>
<body>

<h2>Register</h2>

<form id="registrationForm">
  <label for="name">Name:</label><br>
  <input type="text" id="name" name="name" required><br>
  <label for="email">Email:</label><br>
  <input type="email" id="email" name="email" required><br><br>
  <button type="submit">Submit</button>
</form>

<script>
document.getElementById("registrationForm").addEventListener("submit", function(event){
    event.preventDefault(); // prevent form submission
    var name = document.getElementById("name").value;
    var email = document.getElementById("email").value;
    // Save name and email (you can use AJAX to send this data to a server-side script for saving)
    console.log("Name: " + name + ", Email: " + email);
    alert("Registration successful! Name: " + name + ", Email: " + email);
    // Optionally, you can clear the form fields after submission
    document.getElementById("registrationForm").reset();
});
</script>

</body>
</html>
```

This HTML code creates a simple registration form with fields for name and email. When the form is submitted, it prevents the default form submission behavior, retrieves the values of the name and email fields, logs them to the console, alerts the user with the submitted data, and optionally clears the form fields.
